{
  "A homogeneous mixture is also called a:": "",
  "Solution": "",
  "Element": "",
  "Suspension": "",
  "Compound": "",
  "A homogeneous mixture has a uniform composition throughout and is also known as a solution. The solute is evenly distributed in the solvent at the molecular level, so the mixture looks the same in every part.": "",
  "Which is an example of a heterogeneous mixture?": "",
  "Vinegar": "",
  "Air": "",
  "Salt water": "",
  "Salad": "",
  "A salad is heterogeneous because you can see and separate its individual components (lettuce, tomatoes, croutons). Salt water, air, and vinegar are all examples of homogeneous mixtures (solutions).": "",
  "In a solution, the substance being dissolved is called the:": "",
  "Mixture": "",
  "Solvent": "",
  "Solute": "",
  "The solute is the substance that dissolves (usually present in smaller amount). The solvent is the substance doing the dissolving (usually present in larger amount). In salt water, salt is the solute and water is the solvent.": "",
  "Which of the following is a homogeneous mixture?": "",
  "Oil and water": "",
  "Trail mix": "",
  "Sand and water": "",
  "Vinegar is a homogeneous mixture of acetic acid dissolved in water — it has a uniform appearance throughout. Trail mix is heterogeneous (visible parts), and sand/water and oil/water are heterogeneous (they separate into visible layers).": "",
  "What distinguishes a heterogeneous mixture from a homogeneous one?": "",
  "The parts are visibly different and not uniformly distributed": "",
  "It contains only one type of element": "",
  "It can only exist as a liquid": "",
  "It has a uniform composition throughout": "",
  "Heterogeneous mixtures have a non-uniform composition — you can see distinct regions or components (e.g., salad, trail mix, sand in water). Homogeneous mixtures look the same throughout.": "",
  "Which is the best technique for separating a homogeneous mixture like salt water?": "",
  "Picking by hand": "",
  "Using a magnet": "",
  "Distillation": "",
  "Filtration": "",
  "Distillation separates components by differences in boiling point — you boil the water away and collect it, leaving the salt behind. Filtration works for heterogeneous mixtures with visible solid particles, and magnets only work with magnetic materials.": "",
  "Blood is classified as what type of mixture?": "",
  "Homogeneous": "",
  "Heterogeneous": "",
  "Pure substance": "",
  "Blood contains red blood cells, white blood cells, platelets, and plasma, which can be separated by centrifugation. Although it may look uniform to the naked eye, at the microscopic level it is clearly heterogeneous.": "",
  "Which type of mixture has particles that eventually settle out over time?": "",
  "Colloid": "",
  "A suspension contains large particles that are dispersed but will eventually settle out due to gravity (like muddy water). Solutions have dissolved particles that never settle, and colloids have intermediate particles that stay dispersed.": "",
  "Milk, fog, and gelatin are all examples of:": "",
  "Suspensions": "",
  "Colloids": "",
  "Solutions": "",
  "Pure substances": "",
  "Colloids contain particles larger than those in solutions but smaller than suspensions. They remain dispersed (don't settle) and often scatter light (the Tyndall effect). Milk, fog, and gelatin are classic examples.": "",
  "The substance in a solution that is present in the largest amount is called the:": "",
  "The solvent is the dissolving medium, typically present in the greatest amount. Water is the most common solvent and is called the 'universal solvent' because of its ability to dissolve many substances.": "",
  "What is the definition of a 'mixture'?": "",
  "A single type of atom arranged in a crystal structure": "",
  "Two or more elements bonded in a fixed ratio": "",
  "A chemical reaction that produces new substances": "",
  "A combination of two or more substances that are NOT chemically bonded and can be separated by physical means": "",
  "A mixture is a physical combination of substances that retain their individual properties. Unlike compounds, the components are not chemically bonded, the ratio is variable, and they can be separated by physical means (filtration, distillation, etc.).": "",
  "What does 'homogeneous' mean?": "",
  "Made of particles that settle over time based on established principles": "",
  "Visible to the naked eye, particularly regarding evenly when applying": "",
  "Having a uniform composition throughout — every sample of the mixture has the same proportions": "",
  "Containing only one element, particularly regarding what as typically measured in practice": "",
  "Homogeneous means 'same throughout.' In a homogeneous mixture (solution), the solute is evenly dispersed at the molecular level, so any sample taken from any part of the mixture will have the same composition.": "",
  "What does 'heterogeneous' mean?": "",
  "Having a non-uniform composition — different regions have different proportions of components": "",
  "Made of a single pure substance": "",
  "Living organisms mixed with non-living matter": "",
  "Completely uniform in appearance": "",
  "Heterogeneous means 'different throughout.' The components are not evenly distributed and can often be distinguished visually. A sample from one part may differ from a sample taken from another part.": "",
  "What is a 'colloid'?": "",
  "A mixture with particles larger than a solution but smaller than a suspension, that stay dispersed and don't settle out": "",
  "A pure substance with no dissolved particles": "",
  "A mixture where all particles are individual atoms": "",
  "A chemical compound that dissolves easily in water": "",
  "Colloids have particles sized 1-1,000 nm. They are small enough to stay dispersed (unlike suspensions) but large enough to scatter light (Tyndall effect, unlike solutions). Examples: milk, fog, smoke, mayonnaise, gelatin.": "",
  "What is a 'suspension'?": "",
  "A pure substance in the liquid phase": "",
  "A homogeneous mixture of two liquids": "",
  "A solution with dissolved gases": "",
  "A heterogeneous mixture with large visible particles that will eventually settle out due to gravity": "",
  "Suspensions contain particles larger than 1,000 nm that are visibly dispersed but settle out over time. Muddy water, Italian dressing, and snow globes are examples. They can be separated by filtration.": "",
  "What does 'Tyndall effect' mean?": "",
  "The dissolution of a solute in a solvent": "",
  "The settling of large particles in a suspension over time": "",
  "The scattering of a light beam by particles in a colloid, making the beam visible": "",
  "The separation of a mixture using heat": "",
  "The Tyndall effect is observed when light passes through a colloid — the beam becomes visible because particles scatter the light. It does not occur in true solutions (particles too small) or clear liquids. Think of car headlights visible in fog.": "",
  "What does 'solubility' mean?": "",
  "The ability of a substance to separate from a mixture": "",
  "The maximum amount of solute that can dissolve in a given amount of solvent at a specific temperature": "",
  "The speed at which a solute dissolves": "",
  "The temperature at which a solid melts": "",
  "Solubility is a quantitative measure of how much solute can dissolve in a solvent at a given temperature. For example, about 36 g of NaCl dissolve in 100 mL of water at 25°C. Solubility generally increases with temperature for solids.": "",
  "What does 'filtration' mean?": "",
  "Dissolving a solid completely in a liquid": "",
  "A method of combining two solutions together": "",
  "A separation method that uses a porous barrier to separate solid particles from a liquid or gas": "",
  "Heating a liquid to separate it from dissolved solids": "",
  "Filtration passes a mixture through a filter (paper, cloth, membrane) that allows small particles and liquid to pass through while trapping larger solid particles. It works for heterogeneous mixtures and suspensions but not for solutions.": "",
  "What does 'distillation' mean?": "",
  "A separation technique that uses differences in boiling points — heating to vaporize one component, then cooling to collect it": "",
  "Filtering a mixture through paper to remove solids": "",
  "Adding a chemical to break down a compound": "",
  "Freezing a solution to separate its components": "",
  "Distillation exploits boiling point differences. The mixture is heated until the component with the lower boiling point vaporizes, leaving the other behind. The vapor is then condensed and collected. This can separate solutions (e.g., salt water → pure water + salt).": "",
  "What does 'alloy' mean?": "",
  "A homogeneous mixture of two or more metals (or a metal and a nonmetal), such as brass or steel": "",
  "A pure metal that has been melted and re-solidified": "",
  "A chemical compound containing two metal elements": "",
  "A heterogeneous mixture of different metals": "",
  "An alloy is a solid solution of metals. Brass (copper + zinc), steel (iron + carbon), and bronze (copper + tin) are common examples. Alloys are homogeneous mixtures because the atoms are uniformly distributed throughout.": "",
  "A student shines a flashlight through a glass of lemonade (sugar water + lemon juice) and a glass of whole milk. The beam is invisible in the lemonade but clearly visible in the milk. What explains this difference?": "",
  "Milk is darker in color, which makes the light beam visible": "",
  "The flashlight is not bright enough to pass through lemonade": "",
  "Lemonade absorbs all the light, so none is scattered": "",
  "Milk is a colloid with particles large enough to scatter light (Tyndall effect); lemonade is a true solution with particles too small to scatter light": "",
  "The Tyndall effect occurs in colloids: milk contains fat globules (1-10 μm) that scatter light, making the beam visible. Lemonade is a true solution with dissolved sugar and citric acid molecules too small to scatter visible light.": "",
  "A gold ring is labeled '14 karat,' meaning it is 58.3% gold and 41.7% other metals (copper, silver). Is this a mixture, compound, or pure substance? What type?": "",
  "Pure substance — 14K gold is still classified as pure gold": "",
  "Compound — the metals are chemically bonded in fixed proportions": "",
  "Heterogeneous mixture — you can see separate gold and copper regions": "",
  "Homogeneous mixture (alloy) — the metals are uniformly blended but not chemically bonded": "",
  "14K gold is an alloy — a solid solution of gold with copper, silver, and/or other metals. The metals are physically mixed at the atomic level (homogeneous) but not chemically bonded. The proportions can vary, unlike a compound with fixed ratios.": "",
  "A water treatment plant needs to remove sand, bacteria, and dissolved minerals from river water. What sequence of separation methods would be most effective?": "",
  "Evaporation first, then filtration, particularly regarding solution under the given assumptions": "",
  "Using a magnet, then freezing the water, particularly regarding large when evaluated systematically": "",
  "Distillation alone can remove everything at once when evaluated systematically": "",
  "Filtration (removes sand), then fine filtration or UV treatment (removes bacteria), then distillation or reverse osmosis (removes dissolved minerals)": "",
  "Different contaminants require different methods. Sand (large particles in a suspension) is removed by filtration. Bacteria (microscopic) need fine filtration or UV light. Dissolved minerals (solution) require distillation or reverse osmosis since they pass through regular filters.": "",
  "Italian salad dressing separates into an oil layer on top and a vinegar layer on the bottom after sitting. A student shakes it vigorously and says, 'Now it's a solution!' Is the student correct?": "",
  "No — shaking creates a temporary suspension (or emulsion), but oil and vinegar are immiscible and will separate again": "",
  "Yes — shaking dissolves the oil in the vinegar, creating a solution": "",
  "No — shaking creates a compound by chemically bonding oil and vinegar": "",
  "Yes — the mixture is now homogeneous and will stay mixed permanently": "",
  "Oil (nonpolar) and vinegar (polar) are immiscible — they don't dissolve in each other. Shaking temporarily disperses oil droplets in vinegar, but since they aren't truly dissolved, they will separate again. An emulsifier (like egg yolk in mayonnaise) can stabilize such mixtures.": "",
  "A pharmacist prepares a liquid medicine by adding medication powder to a syrup base. The resulting liquid is completely clear with no visible particles. What type of mixture did the pharmacist create?": "",
  "Compound — mixing created a new chemical substance": "",
  "Heterogeneous mixture — the medication is still separate from the syrup": "",
  "Solution — the medication is fully dissolved and uniformly distributed throughout the syrup": "",
  "Suspension — the particles are just too small to see but will settle": "",
  "If the liquid is completely clear and no particles are visible or settle out, the medication has fully dissolved at the molecular level — this is a solution (homogeneous mixture). If unshaken medicine requires shaking before use, it's a suspension.": "",
  "A student mixes iron filings and sulfur powder in a bowl. He says, 'I can separate them with a magnet, so this is a mixture.' He then heats them strongly and tries the magnet again, but it no longer works. What happened?": "",
  "The heat melted the magnet, so it lost its pull, particularly regarding filings following the established framework": "",
  "Heating turned the mixture into a homogeneous solution when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "Before heating: a heterogeneous mixture separable by magnet. After heating: a chemical reaction formed iron sulfide (FeS), a compound that is no longer magnetic": "",
  "The sulfur evaporated, leaving only non-magnetic iron oxide when measured under controlled conditions": "",
  "Iron filings + sulfur powder is a heterogeneous mixture (physical combination). A magnet attracts the iron because it retains its magnetic property. When heated, iron and sulfur undergo a chemical reaction forming iron sulfide (FeS), a new compound with different properties — including loss of magnetism.": "",
  "A swimming pool appears crystal clear during regular use but turns cloudy after a heavy rainstorm washes in dirt and debris. What classification change occurred to the pool water?": "",
  "It went from a pure substance to a compound": "",
  "It became a colloid because all pools are colloids after rain": "",
  "The water underwent a chemical change and became a different substance": "",
  "It went from a solution (clear, chemicals dissolved) to a suspension/colloid (cloudy, with suspended particles)": "",
  "Clean pool water is a solution — chlorine and other chemicals are dissolved (invisible). After the rainstorm, dirt, clay, and organic particles become suspended in the water, creating a heterogeneous mixture that looks cloudy. The pool filter (filtration) and chemical treatment restore clarity.": "",
  "A survivalist needs to obtain drinkable water from seawater on a deserted island. They have plastic sheeting, a container, and sunlight. Which separation principle should they use?": "",
  "Decanting — letting the water sit will cause the salt to settle to the bottom": "",
  "Freezing — ice formed from seawater is always salt-free": "",
  "Solar distillation — sunlight evaporates the water, which condenses on the plastic and drips into the container, leaving salt behind": "",
  "Filtration — passing seawater through sand will remove the salt": "",
  "Seawater is a solution (salt dissolved in water), so filtration cannot separate them. Solar distillation uses heat to evaporate the water (low boiling point) while the salt (high boiling point) stays behind. The vapor condenses on the cool plastic and drips into the collection container.": "",
  "A factory produces steel, which is an alloy of iron and carbon. The carbon content is precisely controlled at 1.5%. A new employee asks, 'How is this different from iron carbide (Fe₃C), which also contains iron and carbon?' What is the key difference?": "",
  "There is no difference — both are the same substance": "",
  "Steel contains more carbon than iron carbide": "",
  "Steel is a homogeneous mixture (alloy) with variable proportions; iron carbide is a compound with a fixed chemical formula and bonding": "",
  "Steel is a compound and iron carbide is a mixture": "",
  "Steel is a mixture — iron and carbon atoms are physically blended, and the carbon percentage can vary (0.2% to 2.1%). Iron carbide (Fe₃C) is a compound — iron and carbon are chemically bonded in a fixed 3:1 ratio. This distinction between mixture and compound is fundamental in chemistry.": "",
  "A lab technician needs to determine whether an unknown white liquid is a solution, colloid, or suspension. She lets it sit undisturbed for 24 hours (no settling), then shines a laser pointer through it (the beam is clearly visible). What is her conclusion?": "",
  "Cannot determine — more tests are needed": "",
  "Solution — because the particles didn't settle out": "",
  "Suspension — because the light beam was visible": "",
  "Colloid — particles don't settle (rules out suspension) but scatter light (rules out solution)": "",
  "Two key tests distinguish the three types: (1) Settling — suspensions settle, solutions and colloids don't. Since it didn't settle, it's not a suspension. (2) Tyndall effect — colloids scatter light (visible beam), solutions don't. Since the beam was visible, it's a colloid, not a solution.": ""
}